# Video: Defining a Session for Your App

## Learning Objectives
By the end of this video, you’ll be able to:
- Override Honeycomb’s default session ID generator  
- Persist session IDs using browser storage  
- Align session attribution with your app’s user session model  
- Confirm shared session context across user interactions in Honeycomb  

---

### [Visual] Jess looking consfused + trace list with fragmented session IDs for the same user  
**[Audio]**  
Jess, a frontend engineer who is working on a web application called Meminator, has been using Honeycomb to trace user interactions, but something looks off. When she searches for `session.id`, she notices that every time a user refreshes the page or comes back later, Honeycomb shows a brand-new session. That makes it hard for her to follow a user’s journey through her app.

### [Visual] Show Meminator with GO being pressed w/ diagram/abstract visual showing how session IDs are assigned by default with each page load, followed by "override" cue to indicate customization option
**[Audio]**  
Since Honeycomb assigns a new session ID every time the page loads, a user can click “GO” five times, refresh, and click again, and each trace could look unrelated, even though it’s the same user.  

To fix that, we can override the session logic so the traces match how people actually use the app.  

In this video, you’ll learn how to define custom session IDs for your frontend app using the `HoneycombWebSDK` so you can see your user journeys the way you want to in your traces. 

**Source:** [Honeycomb blog: Manage Your Session ID](https://www.honeycomb.io/blog/manage-your-session-id-honeycombs-web-sdk)

### [Visual] Split screen: default (new ID each load) vs. custom (one ID)  
**[Audio]**  
By default, the `HoneycombWebSDK` generates a new ID for every page load.  
This is simple, but it doesn’t reflect how most frontend sessions actually work in Meminator.
Instead, we can define our own logic using the `sessionProvider` property in the `HoneycombWebSDK`.  
**Source:** [Honeycomb blog: Manage Your Session ID](https://www.honeycomb.io/blog/manage-your-session-id-honeycombs-web-sdk)

### [Visual] Code snippet implementing a custom session ID using `sessionProvider` 
**[Audio]**  
Here’s how you do it for Meminator. 
First, let's configure the `sessionProvider` `HoneycombWebSDK` property, which allows us to set the `session.id` by implementing a `getSessionId` method. 
Then, the SDK will store the session ID in the brower's `sessionStorage`, reuse it if it exists, or generate a new one if not.

```js
...
const sdk = new HoneycombWebSDK({
  apiKey: '[YOUR API KEY HERE]', 
  serviceName: '[YOUR APPLICATION NAME HERE]', 
  ... // other config
  sessionProvider: {
      getSessionId: () => {
      return SessionGateway.getSession();
      }
  }
// other config...
});

sdk.start();
```
This ensures a consistent session ID across multiple 'GO' clicks or route changes.

**Source:** [Honeycomb blog: Manage Your Session ID](https://www.honeycomb.io/blog/manage-your-session-id-honeycombs-web-sdk)

### [Visual] Diagram showing two paths: anonymous vs. logged-in  
**[Audio]**  
Now, what if your app needs to handle changes in user state?  
For example, a user may start out anonymous, then log in, or log out later.  
In those cases, you’ll want the old session to end so the trace data doesn’t get mixed together.  

With our `sessionStorage` example, ending a session is as simple as removing the stored ID: `sessionStorage.removeItem('session.id');`

```js
...
const sdk = new HoneycombWebSDK({
  apiKey: '[YOUR API KEY HERE]', 
  serviceName: '[YOUR APPLICATION NAME HERE]', 
  ... // other config
  sessionProvider: {
      getSessionId: () => {
      return SessionGateway.getSession();
      },
      sessionStorage.removeItem('session.id');
  }
// other config...
});

sdk.start();
```
This clears the current session. The next time another span is created, your logic will generate a new `session.id`.

Here are some common cases where expiring a session makes sense:
- A user goes from anonymous to logged in
- A user logs out
- A browser times out the session and logs them out automatically
- A user switches or assumes a new role

By explicitly clearing the stored ID, you make sure Honeycomb data reflects accurate session boundaries.

**Source:** [Honeycomb blog: Manage Your Session ID](https://www.honeycomb.io/blog/manage-your-session-id-honeycombs-web-sdk)

### [Visual] Honeycomb Query Builder with `WHERE session.id = "[some value that makes sense for Meminator]"` and `GROUP BY trace.span_id`  
**[Audio]**  
Now that you’ve set up your custom session ID, let’s make sure it works.  
In Honeycomb, open the Query Builder and add `session.id = "[some value that makes sense for Meminator]` to the WHERE clause, then GROUP BY `trace.span_id`.  This query filters your data to a single session, then groups events by span.

### [Visual] Query results showing five spans linked by the same session.id
**[Audio]**
If a user hit “Go” five times in Meminator, you should see five spans—each from the same session—linked together by the `session.id` you defined.

### [Visual] Trace view with `session.id` highlighted in the span details
**[Audio]**
This confirms the override is working: Honeycomb is grouping user interactions into a single, continuous session.

From here, you can follow a user’s journey end-to-end instead of chasing fragments across multiple sessions.

### [Visual] Recap slide: override, persist, group spans
**[Audio]**
Let’s recap:
- Session IDs help group spans into user journeys that are accurate to they _actually_ use your software
- You can override Honeycomb’s default behavior using   
```js
    sessionProvider: {
      getSessionId: () => {
        return SessionGateway.getSession();
      }
    }
```
- Store the `session.id` where it persists across interactions
- Meaningful session attribution leads to better observability
